{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 08:07:27.445125", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and goals\\n- Detect anomalies affecting reachability of enterprise services.\\n- Localize faulty devices/components.\\n- Identify the most probable root cause(s).\\n- No remediation steps provided.\\n\\nSummary of network health\\n- Core/distribution/access forwarding is healthy: zero packet loss and low RTTs across hosts and server farm subnets.\\n  - Examples: host_1_1_1_1 → 10.200.0.5 (web_server_2): 0% loss, ~2.4 ms avg; host_1_1_1_1 → 10.200.0.8 (DHCP): 0% loss, ~2.1 ms avg.\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 → dns_server (10.200.0.2): 0% loss, ~2.7 ms avg.\\n- HTTP services:\\n  - OK: http://web0.local, http://web1.local, http://web2.local, and http://web99.local (load_balancer) from hosts, with normal TTFB and total times (~1.0–1.3 s).\\n  - FAIL: http://web3.local consistently returns HTTP 000 from both host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1.\\n  - Direct IP to web_server_3 (http://10.200.0.6) succeeds with HTTP 200 from host_1_1_1_1.\\n\\nDetected anomaly\\n- DNS resolution for web3.local is incorrect.\\n  - On both hosts: getent hosts web3.local resolves to 10.1.1.10 (the host_1_1_1_1 client IP), not the server farm IP.\\n  - On the DNS server itself: getent hosts web3.local also returns 10.1.1.10.\\n  - Dig from host_1_1_1_1 against the authoritative DNS (10.200.0.2) returns 10.1.1.10 for web3.local.\\n  - Other records resolve correctly:\\n    - web0.local → 10.200.0.3\\n    - web1.local → 10.200.0.4\\n    - web2.local → 10.200.0.5\\n    - web99.local → 10.200.0.7 (load_balancer)\\n- Impact: HTTP requests to web3.local fail (HTTP 000) because clients attempt to connect to 10.1.1.10 (a host address with no web service) instead of 10.200.0.6 (web_server_3). Service web3.local is effectively unavailable via DNS while reachable by IP.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- Faulty component: DNS server (10.200.0.2), specifically the local zone data for web3.local.\\n- Evidence:\\n  - Authoritative server responds with incorrect A record for web3.local.\\n  - Both clients configured to use DNS 10.200.0.2 inherit and use the same bad answer.\\n  - Routing/OSPF and HTTP service on web_server_3 are not at fault (success via direct IP, healthy ICMP).\\n\\nRoot cause\\n- Misconfigured DNS A record for web3.local in the local zone on the dns_server, pointing to 10.1.1.10 instead of the expected server farm address (10.200.0.6 for web_server_3).\\n- Secondary, minor observation on the DNS server: dig output indicates attempts to query ::1 (IPv6 loopback) with “no servers could be reached” before returning an answer, suggesting a possibly stale/unused IPv6 resolver entry. This did not cause the primary fault but is a configuration irregularity worth noting.\\n\\nAdditional relevant findings\\n- Load balancer host has:\\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 (server farm)\\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (private backend network)\\n  - This matches the design where backend web servers are isolated behind the load balancer (not directly accessible from host subnets).\\n- No evidence of OSPF adjacency or routing issues affecting reachability; end-to-end IP paths are functioning.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The enterprise network forwarding plane is healthy.\\n- Single-service outage is caused by incorrect DNS data: web3.local resolves to a client subnet IP (10.1.1.10) instead of the server farm IP (10.200.0.6). This misconfiguration is on the authoritative DNS server and leads to application-level failure for web3.local while other services remain normal., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='9eaa3a09-d695-43ab-b65a-f102031295d8'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
